    },
    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yes — a few things that keep circling in my head. I don’t think I said clearly enough how alone the whole thing felt at times, even when people were technically \"there.\" I’m a pediatric nurse, so everyone assumed I knew what I wanted and needed; instead I wanted permission to be scared and held. One small moment that mattered was a midwife who sat with me after the birth, no checklist, just held my hand and said, “You did this,” and that felt like oxygen.\n\nI also wish maternity services acknowledged the ripple effects — the precariousness of work, the isolation of rural life, the real need for practical help (meals, a late-night run for diapers, someone to watch the baby for an hour so I could sleep). Screening for mood is fine, but follow-up matters more than a form. Finally, please stop assuming older, experienced women don’t need emotional coaching. I want care that sees the person beneath the resume. That feels important.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 1488,
      "output_tokens": 466
    }
